SIMPLE: matter
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Matter
<hw>Mat"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>matere</ets>, F. <ets>mati⟦egrave⟧re</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>materia</ets>; perh. akin to L. <ets>mater</ets> mother. Cf.
<er>Mother</er>, <er>Madeira</er>, <er>Material</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>That of which anything is composed; constituent substance;
material; the material or substantial part of anything; the constituent
elements of conception; that into which a notion may be analyzed; the
essence; the pith; the embodiment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is the <qex>matter</qex> of virtue.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That of which the sensible universe and all existent
bodies are composed; anything which has extension, occupies space, or is
perceptible by the senses; body; substance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Matter</xex> is usually divided by philosophical
writers into three kinds or classes: <xex>solid</xex>,
<xex>liquid</xex>, and <xex>gaseous</xex>. <xex>Solid</xex> substances
are those whose parts firmly cohere and resist impression, as wood or
stone. <xex>Liquids</xex> have free motion among their parts, and easily
yield to impression, as water and wine. <xex>Gaseous</xex> substances
are elastic fluids, called <xex>vapors</xex> and <xex>gases</xex>, as
air and oxygen gas.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That with regard to, or about which, anything takes
place or is done; the thing aimed at, treated of, or treated; subject of
action, discussion, consideration, feeling, complaint, legal action, or
the like; theme.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧If the <xex>matter</xex> should be tried
by duel.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Son of God, Savior of men! Thy name⟦br⟧
Shall be the copious <qex>matter</qex> of my song.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every great <qex>matter</qex> they shall bring unto thee, but
every small <qex>matter</qex> they shall judge.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xviii.
22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which one has to treat, or with which one has
to do; concern; affair; business.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To help the <qex>matter</qex>, the alchemists call in many
vanities out of astrology.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some young female seems to have carried <qex>matters</qex> so far,
that she is ripe for asking advice.</q>
<rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Affair worthy of account; thing of consequence;
importance; significance; moment; -- chiefly in the phrases <xex>what
matter</xex>? <xex>no matter</xex>, and the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A prophet some, and some a poet, cry;⟦br⟧
No <qex>matter</qex> which, so neither of them lie.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Inducing cause or occasion, especially of anything
disagreeable or distressing; difficulty; trouble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And this is the <qex>matter</qex> why interpreters upon that
passage in Hosea will not consent it to be a true story, that the
prophet took a harlot to wife.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 903 --></p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Amount; quantity; portion; space; -- often
indefinite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Away he goes, . . . a <qex>matter</qex> of seven miles.</q>
<rj><qau>L' Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have thoughts to tarry a small <qex>matter</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Congreve.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No small <qex>matter</qex> of British forces were commanded over
sea the year before.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Substance excreted from living animal bodies; that
which is thrown out or discharged in a tumor, boil, or abscess; pus;
purulent substance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>That which is permanent, or is
supposed to be given, and in or upon which changes are effected by
psychological or physical processes and relations; -- opposed to
<contr>form</contr>.</def> <rj><au>Mansel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>Written manuscript, or anything
to be set in type; copy; also, type set up and ready to be used, or
which has been used, in printing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dead matter</b></col> <fld>(Print.)</fld>, <cd>type which
has been used, or which is not to be used, in printing, and is ready for
distribution.</cd> -- <col><b>Live matter</b></col> <fld>(Print.)</fld>,
<cd>type set up, but not yet printed from.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Matter
in bar</b></col>, <col><b>Matter of fact</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under
<er>Bar</er>, and <er>Fact</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Matter of
record</b></col>, <cd>anything recorded.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Upon the
matter</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Upon the whole
matter</b></col></mcol>, <cd>considering the whole; taking all things
into view; all things considered.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Waller, with Sir William Balfour, exceeded in horse, but were,
<qex>upon the whole matter</qex>, equal in foot.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Matter
<hw>Mat"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Mattered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Mattering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be of
importance; to import; to signify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>matters</qex> not how they were called.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form pus or matter, as an abscess; to
maturate.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Each slight sore
<xex>mattereth</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Matter
<hw>Mat"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To regard as important; to take
account of; to care for.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He did not <qex>matter</qex> cold nor hunger.</q> <rj><qau>H.
Brooke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matterhorn</ent>⟦br⟧
